name: manydata
description: An R package for global governance data
sites_https_justification: Please check the project website as well for further information about the project and partners (https://panarchic.ch/).
description_good_justification: The manydata package offers a succinct README.md document presenting the uses and solutions offered by manydata. It also contains instructional vignettes for the usage of the package.
interact_justification: The manydata project offers instructions in how to report bugs or issues directly in the GitHub address as well as templates for facilitating and standardizing these. Questions, contributions and feedback, as well as other forms of engagement, are encouraged by the developers.
contribution_justification: Projects on GitHub by default use issues and pull requests, as encouraged by documentation such as <https://guides.github.com/activities/contributing-to-open-source/>. manydata encourages contribution and has extensive guidelines on how to contribute to the package development. There are also templates for pull requests to facilitate the engagement of contributors in expected ways (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/blob/main/.github/pull_request_template.md)
contribution_requirements_justification: manydata contains a detailed document on how to contribute and what is expected from contributors (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/blob/main/.github/CONTRIBUTING.md). It also details a code of conduct for future contributors (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/blob/main/.github/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md)
license_location_justification: Non-trivial license location file in repository: <https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/blob/main/LICENSE.md>.
floss_license_justification: The CC-BY-4.0 is used.
floss_license_osi_justification: The CC-BY-4.0 license has not yet been added to the OSI list.
documentation_basics_justification: How to use these specific functions, and others, has been well documented in the vignettes (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/blob/main/vignettes/user.Rmd)
documentation_interface_justification: manydata has a pkgdown webpage that helps to describe and document in detail the package created by the project (https://globalgov.github.io/manydata/).
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: Github works so that we have develop and main branches to merge in-between releases.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_unique_justification: Please check the package news for important information about versioning (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/blob/main/NEWS.md).
version_tags_justification: We use Semantic Versioning to identify releases (see https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/blob/main/NEWS.md).
release_notes_justification: Non-trivial release notes file in repository: <https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/blob/main/NEWS.md>.
release_notes_vulns_justification: Release notes for issues, fixes and additions are detailed for every release and can be found on the package NEWS file.
report_tracker_justification: Check our issues page on GitHub for a list of the issues and their dates (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/issues).
report_process_justification: Users and contributors can report issues, questions and make contributions to the package on GitHub (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/issues).
report_responses_justification: We address bugs rather quickly, whenever possible, when they are found by us or reported to us. Bugs that take a bit longer to address are still acknowledged and made visible with bug tags on our GitHub issues page (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/issues).
enhancement_responses_justification: We meet enhancement requests rather quickly when reported to us via issues or discussions on GitHub. Some of the major enhancement issues we intend to make in the package in the future are put in a timeline with time estimates managed via Zenhub to be worked on in the long term.
report_archive_justification: All of our GitHub issues and discussions are open to the public and trackable even for issue closed via a pull request (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/issues).
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Users and developers can report bugs and other vulnerability issues on our GitHub issues page in a secure and publicly open matter  (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/issues).
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: Reports and checks for package are publicly available.
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: We address issues and bugs rather quickly.
build_justification: We use R and devtools to build packages for use after any changes to code.
build_floss_tools_justification: We use R and GitHub which are free and open source.
test_justification: We develop specific tests for the project code and functions as they are written, for more detail on our tests (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/tree/main/tests/testthat). We also test the package using various test and check mechanisms available on GitHub, for these please check our GitHub workflow page (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/tree/main/.github/workflows).
test_invocation_justification: We develop specific tests for the project code and functions as they are written, for more detail on our tests (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/tree/main/tests/testthat). We also test the package using various test and check mechanisms available on GitHub, for these please check our GitHub workflow page (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/tree/main/.github/workflows).
test_most_justification: As of now, our tests cover most of our code, and we are working towards the goal of getting all of it cover. We provide transparent code coverage reports for tests on our README documentation, please check (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata) for a detailed report on the current code coverage.
test_policy_justification: Our internal policy is that tests are added as package development occurs and any changes are made (test-driven development).
tests_are_added_justification: As you may see on the tests section for qData on GitHub (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/tree/main/tests/testthat) tests are often being added as change occurs.
tests_documented_added_justification: Tests are being added in practice.
warnings_justification: We use linter and other software (pointblank, spellcheck and more) to make sure code is checked before it can be merged into our main branch on GitHub. These tests  are visible as workflows checks on https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/tree/main/.github/workflows.
warnings_fixed_justification: Warnings must be addressed before branch merges are accepted.
warnings_strict_justification: We use many available software that generate informative warnings to developers to check codes before merging.
know_secure_design_justification: Albeit the repository be open source and the code be publicly visible, we have a primary developer who reviews and accepts (or not) any changes made into that a developers branch that are to be merged into the main branch.
know_common_errors_justification: Project maintainer is an experienced developer.
delivery_mitm_justification: Only changes approved by main developer and that pass all automated tests are merged into the main branch.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: We fix issues and vulnerabilities quickly.
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: We fix issues and vulnerabilities quickly.
static_analysis_justification: We use lintr as an extra check for our codes on the workflows (https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/tree/main/.github/workflows).
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: We provide detailed reports and checks for the package before deployment. As well as badges for detailing package language and code coverage.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: Merges are only allowed once the issues pointed in the checks are addressed.
static_analysis_often_justification: For commits in develop or local branches these checks are not necessary since these changes are not yet ready to be implemented in the main package branch. Once any changes are requested to be made to that branch, checks are run on every commit and change is approved only after they pass.
dynamic_analysis_justification: We apply code coverage report tools to account for changes in the percent of the code covered by the tests on every pull request.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: We provide coded languages percentage reports on our GitHub for each package.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: We provide detailed test reports and checks for the package before deployment.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: We always fix issues and vulnerabilities as soon as they arise.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: This process is run constantly locally for development branches and before pull-requests can merged to the main branches of the package. For detailed workflows testing of our package please check https://github.com/globalgov/manydata/tree/main/.github/workflows.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests. Please check manydata on GitHub for more information about open issues and discussions (https://github.com/globalgov/qData/discussions)

name: airshipit
description:
Airshipctl is a command-line interface that enables users to manage declarative infrastructure and software.

Airshipctl aims to provide a seamless experience for operators wishing to leverage the best open source options such as the Cluster API, Metal Kubed, Kustomize, and kubeadm by providing a straight forward and easily approachable interface.
description_good_justification:
Main content of the web site: https://www.airshipit.org/

About Airship

Airship is a collection of loosely coupled but interoperable open source tools that declaratively automate cloud provisioning. Airship is a robust delivery mechanism for organizations who want to embrace containers as the new unit of infrastructure delivery at scale. Starting from raw bare metal infrastructure, Airship manages the full lifecycle of data center infrastructure to deliver a production-grade Kubernetes cluster with Helm deployed artifacts, including OpenStack-Helm. Airship allows operators to manage their infrastructure deployments and lifecycle through the declarative YAML documents that describe an Airship environment.
interact_justification:
https://www.airshipit.org/software/ links to the Git repo https://opendev.org/airship/treasuremap/
https://www.airshipit.org/community/ lists links to feedback and contribution channels.

contribution_requirements_justification: Developers guide https://docs.airshipit.org/airshipctl/developers.html and Contributors guide https://docs.airshipit.org/airshipctl/developers.html#contribution-guidelines are available.
